{
  "text": "Next, we perform an iterated model averaging procedure with an exogenously determined number of maximum control variables to select from. Iterated BMA makes repeated calls to the Bayesian Model Averaging algorithm using the speci\u2026ed maximum number of control variables in every estimated model. After each iteration of BMA only those variables having a posterior inclusion probability greater than 5 % are used for the next step. Clearly, the lower the maximum number of control variables the higher the number of iterations performed. [CITATION_1] The result of the iterated BMA procedure is a list of variables which were selected from the 32 possible controls (including the constant). Table 4 presents the results for three scenarios common in the literature.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "155062687"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "155062687": {
      "title": "Amenities and property values in a model of an urban area",
      "abstract": "The dependence of property values on a schedule of \u2018amenities\u2019 is examined in the case of a \u2018small\u2019 and \u2018open\u2019 city and in the case of a \u2018closed\u2019 city. Questions concerned with the predictability and interpretation of changes in equilibrium property values following an improvement in amenities are considered in these cases. The problem of identifying the implicit demand for amenities from a single equilibrium rent schedule is also addressed."
    }
  }
}